06682nam a22009975i 9780823285815DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232858157 a10.1515/97808232858152doi  a(DE-B1597)555271  a(OCoLC)1178769247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0840002bisacsh00aFundamentalism or Tradition :bChristianity after Secularism /ced. by Aristotle Papanikolaou, George E. Demacopoulos. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOrthodox Christianity and Contemporary Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Being as Tradition -- tSecularization -- tSecularism: The Golden Lie -- tCollectivistic Christianities and Pluralism: An Inquiry into Agency and Responsibility -- tWhat Difference Do Women Make? Retelling the Story of Catholic Responses to Secularism -- tThe Secular Pilgrimage of Orthodoxy in America -- tSaeculum– Ecclesia– Caliphate: An Eternal Golden Braid -- tA Secularism of the Royal Doors: Toward an Eastern Orthodox Christian Theology of Secularism -- tFundamentalism -- tFundamentalism: Not Just a Cautionary Tale -- tResolving the Tension between Tradition and Restorationism in American Orthodoxy -- tFundamentalists, Rigorists, and Traditionalists: An Unorthodox Trinity -- t“Orthodoxy or Death”: Religious Fundamentalism during the Twentieth and Twenty- first Centuries -- tConfession and the Sacrament of Penance after Communism -- tConscience and Catholic Identity -- tFundamentalism as a Preconscious Response to a Perceived Threat -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraditional, secular, and fundamentalist—all three categories are contested, yet in their contestation they shape our sensibilities and are mutually implicated, the one with the others. This interplay brings to the foreground more than ever the question of what it means to think and live as Tradition. The Orthodox theologians of the twentieth century, in particular, have emphasized Tradition not as a dead letter but as a living presence of the Holy Spirit. But how can we discern Tradition as living discernment from fundamentalism? What does it mean to live in Tradition when surrounded by something like the “secular”? These essays interrogate these mutual implications, beginning from the understanding that whatever secular or fundamentalist may mean, they are not Tradition, which is historical, particularistic, in motion, ambiguous and pluralistic, but simultaneously not relativistic.Contributors: R. Scott Appleby, Nikolaos Asproulis, Brandon Gallaher, Paul J. Griffiths, Vigen Guroian, Dellas Oliver Herbel, Edith M. Humphrey, Slavica Jakelić, Nadieszda Kizenko, Wendy Mayer, Brenna Moore, Graham Ward, Darlene Fozard Weaver  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aPolitical Science. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aAppleby, R. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAppleby, R. Scott.1 aAsproulis, Nikolaos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsproulis, Nikolaos.1 aDemacopoulos, George E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemacopoulos, George E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFozard Weaver, Darlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFozard Weaver, Darlene.1 aGallaher, Brandon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallaher, Brandon.1 aGriffiths, Paul J.1 aGriffiths, Paul J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re